# Story Format (Gherkin + NFRs)

All user stories and acceptance criteria in this project **must** be written in **Gherkin format**.

## Gherkin structure
- Use `Feature`, `Scenario` (or `Scenario Outline`), `Given`, `When`, `Then` (and optionally `And`, `But`).
- One feature per user story; scenarios are acceptance criteria.
- **Example:** Use **normal Gherkin narrative** for the feature and user story lines; use the **table** only for each **Scenario** (acceptance criterion).

**Feature and narrative (normal text, not a table):**

```gherkin
Feature: [Short feature name]

  As a [role]
  I want [goal]
  So that [benefit]
```

**Each acceptance criterion (scenario)—tabular steps**

| # | Keyword | Content |
|---|---------|---------|
| 1 | `Scenario:` | [Scenario name] |
| 2 | `Given` | [precondition] |
| 3 | `When` | [action] |
| 4 | `Then` | [observable outcome] |

*(Repeat the scenario table for each acceptance criterion; use `And` / `But` as extra rows with the same keyword column when needed.)*

Each technical task or sub-task that has acceptance criteria should also use Gherkin if applicable.

## Non-functional requirements (NFRs)
- **Only When applicable**, add NFRs explicitly. Do not force NFRs onto every story; add them where they matter (e.g. performance, security, accessibility, scale).
- NFRs can be written as:
  - Gherkin-style scenarios (e.g. `Scenario: Response time under load` with Given/When/Then), or
  - Short, testable statements (e.g. "Page must meet WCAG 2.1 AA" or "P95 latency < 200ms").
- Prefer one NFR section or scenario per concern so they are traceable.

## Jira field mapping & defaults
When publishing stories to Jira, see `.cursor/defaults.md` (section "Jira Story Defaults") for field mapping and default values.
